Thus writes Pallas, and do thou, her Cyprian sister, read; likewise thy boy should hear the indictment preferred against you both. 'Tis no old offences, such as led to the tragedy of Troy, that 1 complain ol, nor thy favours to Mars and to Adonis: thy own husband [Vulcan] can deal with these. What 1 complain of is violence and violated rights and torches introduced into my sortress. The youths that 1 have selected for study are assailed by the darts ol Cupid, and the myrtle takes the place of the laurel. Hence, with this tide of marriages, thou art encroaching on my domain. Nuptials I disregard, and so do the Muses, who disown, as witness Pyreneus, the rule ol thee and thy son. True, there is some pleasure in domestic bliss and listening to the broken lispings of some young prattler. Yet every such sweet has its sour.
